w:r.w:t: Quantifying and visualising divergence between pairs of phylogenetic trees

Tree topologies are the primary output of phylogenetic analysis. It is important to understand how this output responds to parameters such as the nature and quality of input data (whether morphological or molecular data) and the choice of phylogenetic method. This often requires the measurement of how closely an output corresponds to an ideal tree topology, but existing metrics offer at best a limited answer to this question, not least because few explicitly address the inevitable trade-off between accuracy and precision that arises when trees may contain polytomies.
Here I propose a divergence metric based on quartet statements that can be applied to any pair of tree topologies

, whilst avoiding the shortcomings of many widely-used methods. Ternary diagrams effectively depict the contributions of accuracy and precision to this tree similarity measure. I demonstrate a case study in which this new approach generates alternative conclusions. The method
implemented in a new package for the R statistical environment.
